sec.p:
Sample size estimation was based on the frequency of AEs. According to research from the Eleventh Five-Year Plan Science and Technology Support, the frequency of acute exacerbations per year for COPD patients with lung function grade 3 was 0.77 times/year in the Chinese medicine treatment group and 1.30 times/year in the standard Western medicine treatment group, with a difference of 0.53 times/year between the two groups. Sample estimation was calculated according to the sample size estimation formula for the comparison of the mean (equal number of cases) of two samples: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$n = 2\left[ {\frac{{(\mu_{\alpha } + \mu_{\beta } )\sigma }}{\delta }} \right]^{2}$$\end{document}n=2(μα+μβ)σδ2. Setting α = 0.05 (two-sided test) and β = 0.10, and assuming a reduction of 0.53 acute exacerbations per year in the TCM group compared to the Western medicine group, the sample size for each group was estimated to be n = 117, based on a bilateral cut-off value of δ = 0.53 and an estimated sample variance of 1.25. Considering a 20% dropout rate, the required sample size per group was adjusted to 141, with a total sample size of 282 cases for both lung function grade 3 and grade 4 patients.
